post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_12798395_12798436_0": {"length": 20, "quality": 0.9523809523809523, "section_id": 7214}}, "n3337": {"so_12798395_12798436_0": {"length": 20, "quality": 0.9523809523809523, "section_id": 6958}}, "n4659": {"so_12798395_12798436_0": {"length": 20, "quality": 0.9523809523809523, "section_id": 8723}}}, "12798395": {"ViewCount": "825", "Body": "<p>I have to input a string into an unsigned short array.</p>\n<p>Here is my implementation:</p>\n<pre><code>unsigned short strFile [ 200 ] = {0};\ncin &gt;&gt; strFile;\n</code></pre>\n<p>I have included the <code>iostream.h</code> header.</p>\n<p>But I always get an error: </p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_12798395_12798395_0\">error C2678: binary '&gt;&gt;' : no operator found which takes a left-hand operand of type 'std::istream'</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Anybody knows how should I solve this?</p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "12798436", "Title": "Input a string into an unsigned short array in C++", "CreationDate": "2012-10-09T10:47:00.760", "Id": "12798395", "CommentCount": "5", "LastEditDate": "2014-09-18T09:23:48.433", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "2642204", "LastActivityDate": "2014-09-18T09:23:48.433", "Score": "-1", "OwnerUserId": "1706063", "Tags": "<c++>", "AnswerCount": "1"}, "12798436": {"Id": "12798436", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>There is no kind of string that would be compatible with <code>unsigned short[]</code>.</p>\n<p>There is normal string that is <code>char []</code> (in C++ you should always keep it in <code>string</code> except for constants!) and wide string, that is <code>wchar_t[]</code> (in C++ you should always keep it in <code>wstring</code>). And C++11 adds <code>char16_t</code> and <code>char32_t</code> and their corresponding <code>u16string</code> and <code>u32string</code>.</p>\n<p>You can read normal string from normal input stream like <code>cin</code>. You can read wide string from <em>wide</em> input stream like <code>wcin</code>.</p>\n<p><code>wchar_t</code> used to be typedef to <code>unsigned short</code> in C, but C++ requires it to be a separate type. ISO/IEC\n14882:2003 3.9.1/5:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_12798395_12798436_0\">Type <code>wchar_t</code> is a distinct type whose values can represent distinct codes for all members of the largest extended character set specified among the supported locales (22.1.1).</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "201725", "LastActivityDate": "2012-10-10T05:47:52.843", "Score": "3", "CreationDate": "2012-10-09T10:49:19.070", "ParentId": "12798395", "CommentCount": "1", "LastEditDate": "2012-10-10T05:47:52.843", "OwnerUserId": "201725"}});